{
  "doc_id": "48018",
  "text": "In contrast to many protein kinases, GSK-3 is active in resting cells and is inactivated by phosphorylation. [CITATION_1] On stimulation, GSK-3 is phosphorylated at serine 21 in GSK-3␣ or serine 9 in GSK-3␤, resulting in inhibition of GSK-3 kinase activity. [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] PKB phosphorylates GSK-3 at both of these sites in vitro and in vivo. [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] Inhibition of GSK-3␤ has been shown to reduce apoptosis and enhance cell survival, [CITATION_7] providing a plausible mechanism by which phosphorylation and inhibition of GSK-3␤ might mediate cardioprotection. Several groups have reported that a dominant-negative GSK-3␤ or inhibitors of GSK-3␤ prevent apoptosis. [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] However, the precise mechanism by which GSK-3␤ inhibits apoptosis is not clear. GSK-3 was originally identified as an enzyme that regulates glycogen synthesis in response to insulin. [CITATION_10] Recent studies have demonstrated a growing list of substrates for GSK-3␤, such as ␤-catenin, tau, NF-AT, cyclin D1, c-myc, E-cadherin, and eIF2B, 10 some of which may be involved in GSK inhibition of apoptosis. Data in Figure 2B show that at the start of sustained ischemia, GSK-3␤ activity is significantly lower in PC versus non-PC hearts. During ischemia, GSK-3␤ is inhibited in non-PC as well as PC hearts, but there is a trend toward lower activity in PC hearts. These data suggest that the lower GSK-3␤ activity at the start of the sustained ischemia is protective.",
